observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the
LCE
(a) utilize optimally the 20% DF to help achieve the desirable socio-economic development and environmental outcomes of the LGU;
(b) instruct the head of the City Urban Planning and Development Office (CUPDO) to closely monitor the progress of implementation of PPAs included in the AIP;
(c) instruct the Implementing Offices to implement the developmental projects in accordance with their targeted/planned time frame; and
(d) require the CA to correctly classify the abovementioned disbursements to their appropriate accounts, moving forward.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the head of CENRO to 

(a) strictly implement wastes segregation at source; 


(b) consider the application of appropriate sanctions if sorting by household is not done; 


(c) closely monitor the solid waste practices of barangays without MRF; and 

(d) limit the expenditures for hauling by setting a certain quota or limit of truckload per day for each barangay depending on the existing population and livelihood.

We recommended that the City Mayor 

(a) consider constructing a central storage area/ stockroom to house all deliveries of supplies; 

(b) require the property/ supply custodians to make use of RIS for every withdrawal/issuance of supplies from CGSO and submit to City Accounting Office the MRSI; 


(c) submit the inventory report on supplies every semester; 



(d)  maintain stock cards/ subsidiary records for individual items on stock; and 

(e)   secure fidelity bond for all its property accountable officers.

We recommended that the City Mayor 

(a) strictly enforce anti-littering ordinances, create anti littering brigades in barangays and employ other strategies to counteract the uncontrolled dumping of wastes along main roads and waterways; 

(b) request for another trash boat from DENR to service the opposite area towards Barangay Liputan; 

(c) install CCTVs in appropriate places to monitor movement of people and vehicles dumping garbage anywhere; 

(d) post additional signboards for the schedule of garbage collection per type of wastes; and 


(e) instruct the CAO to record the receipt of one-unit boat from DENR amounting to ₱300,000.00.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the 

(a) GAD Focal Person to assign dedicated personnel to coordinate regularly with the Budget and Accounting Offices to properly monitor and reconcile charges for PPAs contained in GPB and the Budget/Accounting Records; 

(b) submit the supporting documents and the liquidation reports for all GAD expenditures/ attributions; 

(c) set up a GAD database which will serve as basis for planning, formulating policies, implementing, monitoring and evaluating GAD responsive PPAs; and 

(d) the City Budget and Accounting Offices to maintain a registry of GAD allotment/expenditures /schedule/ subsidiary ledgers for GAD PPAs to ensure proper monitoring and reconciliation of the GAD fund records with the GFP.

We recommended that the City Mayor require the OIC City Engineer to

(a) closely coordinate with PNR to expedite the issuance of the Official Security Pass for the implementation of the project; 
(b) conduct detailed engineering particularly the site inspection and survey/inquiry for every project before procurement activities are conducted;  

(c) assign a project engineer and project inspector for each project for proper monitoring and implementation; 

(d) strictly supervise the implementation of programmed projects in accordance with the target date of completion; and 

(e) consider realignment of the funds for the unimplemented project due to failure to secure the deed of donation.

We recommended that Management require the officials concerned to:

(a) require the officials concerned to optimize  the utilization of DF for PPA under its ADP ; 

(b) expedite the implementation of all developmental projects  identified in the  Annual Investment Program for the  timely completion of all  the   programmed socio- economic development and environmental projects  of the City  pursuant to JMC No. 2017 -1 dated February 22, 2017;

(c) take immediate priority action on the PPAs needing realignment to avoid delays in the implementation of PPAs programmed for future undertakings; 

(d) determine the cost of actual accomplishments of  all the unfinished projects and compute for the liquidated damages to be imposed to the contractor equal to at least one tenth (1/10) of one (1) percent of the cost of the  unperformed  portion of the works  for every day of delay;  and 

(e) particularly the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to   furnish invitation letters to at least two additional observers aside from COA, strictly comply with the requirement of invitation in all stages of the procurement and post the bidding documents in the agency’s website; and (f) submit the lacking documentary requirements to the COA Auditor such as the ABC, Original and As-Built Plans, SWA, POW and Detailed Estimate with Unit Cost Derivation.

We recommended that Management 

(a) direct the CEEMO to coordinate with the developer of the public market for the submission of legal documents to document  any change in the  ownership  of the latter in order that the City may be properly guided in transacting with them; 

(b)   require the developer to inform the City of any adjustments made in the rentals and charges to the tenants of the market; 

(c) direct the officials concerned to be diligent on the civil case filed for the expropriation of lot in the transport terminal in order to protect the City’s interest and avoid the risk of losing the City’s investment in the development of the terminal; and  

(d) execute lease agreements/rental contracts with the concerned stallholders of the canteen to enforce obligations of both parties.

We recommended that Management require the: 

(a) City Accounting Office to recognize in the books  the Medical Equipment   and Disaster Equipment  amounting to ₱2,438,000.00 and   P420,000.00, respectively;  

(b) City General Services Officer  and the City Assessor to  Confirm with the Registry of Deeds or Land Registration Authority the City’s  ownership of land covered by the land titles indicated in the physical inventory, tax declaration and  exert efforts to secure the land titles for untitled lots;

(c) Inventory Committee to complete the physical count of all PPE and expedite  the  submission of the physical inventory report; and  

(d)  the General Service Office to maintain Property Cards  and  the Accounting Office to  maintain Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards   for easy reconciliation of records.

We recommended that the 

(a) CSWDO conduct actual validation of the  families and individuals in the affected barangays to come up with the victim profiles/database; 

(b) submit to CDRRMO the provision for data base generation of disaster victims, relief goods  and temporary shelter for inclusion in the AIP for DRRMF;  

(c) CDRRMO prepare the LDRRMP and  involve the CSWDO and other concerned offices in the AIP  deliberation to include database generation, stockpile of relief goods,  provision of temporary shelter  and ensure appropriateness of procurement for disaster need; and 

(d) City Engineering Office and  in joint coordination with the Bureau of Fire Protection, conduct fire prevention inspection of business establishments,  residential areas and other public places.

We recommended that Management require the 

(a) BAC and GSO to ensure that procured medicines do not exceed the one quarter requirement; 

(b)  CHO and CHUs to conduct regular inventory of medicines taking into consideration the required minimum shelf life and  to properly keep, store, and account for the medicines by assigning permanent personnel to handle the storage rooms for proper accountability; 

(c) City Accounting Office to recognize the procurement of drugs and medicines as  inventories;   

(d) GSO to impose penalty for late delivery of medicines  under P.O. No. 2017-12-017 dated December 15, 2017 issued to  Synapse Trading amounting to ₱15,764,374.50; and 

(e) the requisitioning officer attach the  certification that the medicines being  procured fall within and conform with the latest edition of the PNF Manual.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 

(a) instruct the Solid Waste Management Board to cause the speedy preparation of the City Solid Waste  Management Plan and its supporting documents as their basis in the effective implementation of solid waste management; 

b) encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes; 

(c) comply with the requirements of the law on waste segregation by placing trash bins with proper labels and by collecting only the garbage that is properly segregated; 

(d) provide necessary support in the establishment of MRFs at the Barangays; 

(e) cause the closure of open dump/s in the barangay to prevent hazards to the environment; and 

(f) recommend to the Sangguniang Panglungsod (SP) policies and possible measures that will ensure full compliance by the barangays on the provisions of R.A. No. 9003.

We recommended that Management 

(a) devise a more advanced/modern strategies and measures for the efficient and effective operation of the terminal to generate more revenues for the benefit of its constituents; 

(b) execute lease agreements or rental contracts  with the concerned transport groups to strictly enforce obligations between parties, and for security purposes;   

(c) implement the issuance of parking tickets to all vehicles upon entry for proper reconciliation with the collection records or official receipts issued; and 

(d) install/provide Public Address System Facilities and CCTV Cameras for an adequate monitoring of the premises.

We recommended that Management 

(a)  effect the immediate and complete reconciliation of the PPE records, to verify and analyze the discrepancies noted and to arrive at the correct balances of PPE accounts;

(b) instruct the Accounting Office to prepare and maintain Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards for each item of PPE; 

(c) instruct the GSO to include in the RPCPPE  acquisitions made in CY 2016 and to maintain Property Cards for each item of PPE to support the details of the reported inventory; and 

(d) submit to COA Office additional documents to support the disposal of unserviceable property in order to determine the actual value of the disposed properties and the reasonableness of the proceeds therefrom.

We recommended that Management 
(a) strictly comply with the pertinent provisions of R. A. No. 9184 on Public Bidding to ensure transparency in the procurement process and faithful compliance of the project; 

(b) submit the relevant documents to establish validity of the claims for payment; 

(c) require the concerned officials to affix their signatures on pertinent documents to establish responsibility to the transactions; and 

(d) undertake immediate measures for the full restoration and maintenance of the elevator in order to save on unnecessary expenditures for its repairs and to prevent  damage and adverse consequences on the City’s employees, its clients and constituents, specifically the aged ones.

We recommended that Management instruct the Accounting and GSO 

(a)  together with the Inventory Committee to facilitate the completion of the physical count of all PPE items reported and recorded in the inventory report and the books; 

(b) to prepare and maintain property and equipment ledger cards to be the correct basis for reconciliation of property account; 

(c) investigate the causes for the missing /unaccounted motor vehicle assigned to the SP and determine the person/s  liable therefor; and 


(d) immediately request for disposal of the unserviceable assets to prevent further deterioration.

We recommended that the City Mayor 

(a) evaluate the necessity of the services of all non-regular/ plantilla employees with a view of retaining only those who are qualified and meet the needs of the City to avoid the incurrence of unnecessary expenses; 
(b) see to it that those hired under job orders are contracted for a limited period, as dictated by the necessity of the services, not exceeding six months;

c) observe the conditions and procedures provided by existing laws, rules and regulations in hiring consultants; and 

(d) instruct the HRMO to require the submission of accomplishment reports from job order personnel and  curriculum vitae and list of deliverables/outputs from consultants and furnish copy thereof to the Audit Team; and

(e) direct the City Accountant to review claims with diligence by considering the checklist of requirements as per COA Memorandum No. 2005-027 dated February 28, 2005, COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 and the RIRR of R.A. No. 9184.

We recommended that Management 

(a) strictly implement the provisions of  IRR of R.A. No. 9184 specifically on the implementation of various projects in the future;  

(b) submit to Audit Team for evaluation copies of required documents for review of contracts;  


(c) include the provision on the imposition of the liquidated damages in the contract agreement as required in R.A. No. 9184; and 


(d) instruct the BAC to desist from issuing Resolutions for the approval of extension of contract time and other actions which are not among its functions.
